For my own part, considering the extent of work that was completed at the early period we are contemplating, and the character of the same, it seems utterly impossi- ble, allowing for' the slenderness of the as yet existing means of the Convent, to account for the fact that it was effected, on any other ground save some such as that now suggested. The effort, and the results alike, were so obviously beyond the means and the unassisted power of the Convent, and the assistant must have been one alike inunificent and abounding in wealth.
